                Fourth &#45;cover page......................................................&#36;1500<lb/></p>
                
            <p>Copy must be received six weeks in advance of sate of publication&#58; thus&#44; for March MAGAZINE copy must be not later than January 15.<lb/></p>
            <p>HARPER&#39;S WEEKLY&#58; Per line&#44; each insertion&#44; Inside&#44; &#36;1 50; Outside&#44; &#36;2 00. Closes Friday at 9 A.M.<lb/></p>
            <p>HARPERS BAZAR&#58; Per line&#44; each insertion &#36;1 00. Closes Saturday at 9 A.M.<lb/></p>
            <p>HARPER&#39;S YOUNG PEOPLE&#58; COVER PAGES&#44; per line&#44; each insertion&#44; 50 cents. Closes Wednesday at 9 A.M.<lb/></p>
            <p>Special Reading Notices in WEEKLY or BAZAR&#44; &#36;2 00 per line.		Average&#44; eight words to a line&#59;; twelve lines to an inch.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>N.K. BARNUM&#44; ADVERTISING AGENT.<lb/></p>
            <p>Address&#58; Care of HARPER &#38; BROTHERS&#44; FRANKLIN SQUARE&#44; NEW YORK.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>July 27 1885<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev S  Morais D.D.<lb/>
                Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>My friend E W Arnold Esq<lb/> of N.Y. tells me that you are an emine&#45;<lb/>nt Hebrew Scholar &#38; that I can use his<lb/> name to write you. So I take the liberty<lb/> to ask you to give me the proper rendering<lb/> from the original Hebrew of the the word<lb/> &#34;Raven&#34; as it occurs I Kings 17<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 6 verse<lb/> from my limited stand it <sic>seemes</sic> to me<lb/> it should be arabins&#44; or more properly<lb/> &#34;Arabs&#44;&#34; but those who are more in the<lb/> Miracelons&#91;&#63;&#93; contend the word is<lb/> properly translated &#34; Ravens&#34;. You can<lb/> answer at your convenience.<lb/></p>
            <p>With great respect  Yours truly<lb/>
                &#91;stamped in blue ink&#93; N.K. BARNUM.<lb/></p>
            <p>29 Halsey St Brooklyn NY.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>Without denying the Author of Nature the power to use His creatures as He wills&#44; I<lb/>  am personally inclined to your opinion. In fact&#44; the question is discussed in the Talmud &#40; Treatise Holin&#91;&#63;&#93; p 5&#41;&#44; and<lb/> views are there expressed &#94; as to the possibility that the historian may have meant by &#34;Arebim&#34; men from the fortress of &#34;Areb&#34;.<lb/> &#40;See Judges VII. 25&#41;.  Still&#44; the discussion favors the general rendition&#59; nor can it be denied that the punct<lb/>uators understood the word so&#44; for they <del>connected with its</del> attached to its consonants such vowel&#45;points as might make the <del>word</del> Hebrew term<lb/> read &#94; &#40;Arebim&#41; &#34;Ravens&#34; <del>&#40;Arebim&#41;</del> whereas the vowels for <hi rend="underline">Arabs</hi> would be different  <del>and the word is Hebrew</del> we would read them<lb/> <del>would read</del> Arabiyini &#94; and not rebim. The whole chapter &#40; I Kings XVII&#41; evidences a  wish on the part of the<lb/> narrator to present Elijah as a being for whose sake nature <del>would be</del> was diverted from her course.<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours respectfully<lb/>
                S. Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>July 28&#47; 85<lb/></p>
                
                
                
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>July 28&#91;&#44;&#93; 1885<lb/></p>
                
            <p>In answer to a man with Harper&#39;s about<lb/> the word translated Raven.<lb/>
                Dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Without denying the Author of Nature<lb/> the power to use his creation as He wills&#44; I am<lb/> personally inclined to your opinion. In fact the<lb/> question is discussed in the Talmud &#40;treatise...&#41;<lb/> and views are there expressed as to the possibility<lb/> that the historian may have meant by &#34;Arebim&#34; men<lb/> from the fortress of &#34;Areb&#34; &#40;Judges...&#41; Still the<lb/> &#45;&#45;&#45; favors the general rendition&#59; nor can it be<lb/> denied that the translators understood the word so&#44; for<lb/> they attached to its consonants such vowel points as<lb/> might make the Hebrew term read &#40;&#34;Arebim&#34;&#41; &#34;Ravens&#34;<lb/>&#45;&#45; the vowels for Arabs would be different<lb/> we  would read them Arabiyini and not Arebim.  The whole<lb/> chapter &#40;I Kings XVII&#41; evidence a wish on the part<lb/> of the narrator to present Elijah as a being for<lb/> whose sake nature was diverted from her course&#91;.&#93;</p>
            <p>Yours respectfully<lb/>
                <sic>signde</sic><lb/></p>
